# agents.slice — user-scope memory ceiling for interactive agent CLI processes
# (claude/codex/cursor/gemini/etc). Part of bead ez-gh-actions-0725 (panel
# decision recorded on ez-gh-actions-ah94, Tier 1 do-now item #2).
#
# HOW A PROCESS JOINS THIS SLICE (opt-in, nothing auto-migrates):
#   scripts/host/agent-cli-scoped.sh <command> [args...]
# which runs `systemd-run --user --slice=agents.slice --scope -- <command>`.
# This unit only needs to exist under ~/.config/systemd/user/ for that to
# work — systemd auto-starts a slice the first time a scope/service
# references it. No `systemctl --user enable` step is required or performed
# by this repo's install path; see install.sh comments near the auxiliary
# unit loop for why this unit is intentionally NOT swept into the
# `ezgha-*.service`/`ezgha-*.timer` glob (it is a host-wide concern, not
# ezgha-fleet-specific, and must stay opt-in per the panel's "don't
# force-migrate any live session" instruction).
#
# WHY MemoryHigh (not MemoryMax): MemoryHigh is a *soft* ceiling — the
# kernel throttles the cgroup and aggressively reclaims its reclaimable
# memory (page cache first, then swaps out anonymous pages) once usage
# exceeds the threshold, but it does NOT invoke the OOM killer against
# member processes. That is the deliberate choice here: a safety mechanism
# must not itself cause the outage it's meant to prevent (repo CLAUDE.md
# "Self-Outage Prevention Principle") — a hard MemoryMax on a live coding
# agent's cgroup would SIGKILL agents outright, turning a memory-pressure
# warning into forced session loss, which is worse than the degrade-and-
# slow-down behavior MemoryHigh gives you.
#
# BLAST RADIUS / NORMAL PEAK / SAFE MARGIN (required by repo CLAUDE.md
# "Safety & Monitoring Principles" for any new threshold):
#   - Normal peak observed (2026-07-08 through 2026-07-10 incident window):
#     host squeezed to ~14GB of headroom outside the Colima VM (which holds
#     a static 48GiB/24cpu allocation of the 62GB host total, out of scope
#     for this bead) across ~25-29 concurrent claude/codex/agent CLI
#     processes plus the ezgha daemon and system processes. That ~14GB
#     window is what pegged the 16GB swapfile at 99-100% utilization for
#     multiple days, produced D-state process pileup, and spiked load
#     average to 218, triggering a watchdog reboot on 2026-07-10 that
#     killed an in-progress agent session.
#   - MemoryHigh=20G leaves roughly 6GB of throttling headroom above that
#     observed ~14GB peak before this slice starts reclaiming/throttling
#     its own member processes. It is deliberately NOT set at or below the
#     observed peak — the goal is to catch runaway growth *beyond* what has
#     already been observed as "normal but uncomfortable," not to throttle
#     the fleet's steady-state operation and cause a second, self-inflicted
#     degradation.
#   - This ceiling applies ONLY to processes explicitly launched via
#     agent-cli-scoped.sh into this slice — it has zero effect on the
#     ezgha daemon, the Colima VM, or any process not opted in.
#
# Static syntax validation only (no live start/enable performed by this
# commit): `systemd-analyze verify systemd/agents.slice`

[Unit]
Description=Interactive agent CLI processes (claude/codex/cursor/etc) — soft memory ceiling
Before=slices.target

[Slice]
MemoryHigh=20G
MemoryAccounting=yes
